Oleksandra_Aliyeva 17-Jan-22 09:43 AM
Hi. When you are defining function, do a newList before your for loop. I think newList can‚Äôt be in the loop. Like this: def listSearcher(list): newList = [] for oregano in list: if oregano > list[1]: newList.append(oregano) return newList (edited)

Hey Ryan, your code looks good, Oleksandra_Aliyeva already figured about the statement within the loop so, you have to put it before the loop starts or it will iterate again and again and initialize it to an empty list. Additionally, as you are returning something you need to assign it to some variable to print it. So you can do returned_list = listSearcher(a_list). Mandy_Sachs 22-Jan-22 11:39 AM
Hey all! For us TAs, a lot of the time the best way for us to evaluate the problems you run into and help you is to first get some time viewing your notebook(s) on our own before we are ready to help. In order to do this, you need to make it so that anyone with the link can view, as the default is restricted. Quick little tutorial here: 1) Click Share in the upper righthand corner 2a) In the second box, where it says ‚ÄúGet link,‚Äù Click the hyperlink which says ‚ÄúChange to anyone with the link.‚Äù This will automatically change the setting for you. 2b) If you are using an account that is tied to a business or else, you can click on the link icon, then click on ‚ÄúRestricted‚Äù to open up a drop down menu. From here, click ‚ÄúAnyone with the link‚Äù 3) Click ‚ÄúCopy link‚Äù or click in the box where the link is and copy however you like the best (CTRL + C or Right Click + Copy). Then paste it in a message! I know mostly everyone is new to Google Colab, so I wanted to share with you all as a group how you can help us help you! I also made a video for you to follow along if that is easier for you rather than reading the steps above (edited)

Mandy_Sachs 23-Jan-22 07:55 AM
Not that I am aware of. I have just learned stuff as I have used it more. Google colab mostly just follows python structure, and python does not support commenting out multiple lines at once. Sadly you will need to manually do a # before each line. OR may I suggest, if you are going to write out something, do not use comments. instead do the +Text and write it out separately. This does not interfere with running your code and can be really helpful to use intermittently within your code blocks. For other markdowns (things you can do to make your notebook pop) here's a lil cheat sheet I found online https://colab.research.google.com/github/Tanu-N-Prabhu/Python/blob/master/Cheat_sheet_for_Google_Colab.ipynb
Google Colaboratory

5) The club decides to sell the leftover items at half price and everything quickly sells out! Determine how much money was collected from the clearance sale. 6) How much total money was collected from the bake sale (including the sale of full price and clearance items)?
Ryan_Masters 24-Jan-22 08:53 AM
So for 5) you'll have to assign a new list (leftover_list or whatever) that corresponds with your quantity list (so for items that don't have leftovers, you need to include 0 so that the indexing stays the same). Trickiest part of this is remembering/re-reading what baked good is assigned to each indexof the list. Then you want to do some math to calculate the sales of these items (so your leftovers multiplied by your price_array adjusted to half-off). 6) Will take the sales results of 5) and add it to the original collected monies. Make sense?

Alexis_Deviney
if distance is NumPy array, what is the difference between these two ways of calling min/max functions? Is one way preferable?
Instructor_JamesI 24-Jan-22 04:42 PM
Hey @Alexis_Deviney! The two different ways are equivalent. The way that says distance.max() is using the .max() method and np.max(distance)is using the np.max function.

Oleksandra_Aliyeva 25-Jan-22 10:55 AM

Ryan_Masters
I'm working through the pandas assignment where we use .fillna() to fill the NaN values in the column '2021 Counts.' For some reason if I specify the column name in the series, the DF returns just the filled column. The NaN's only fill if I don't specify a column. What am I missing?
Mandy_Sachs 25-Jan-22 10:57 AM
do you have a snippet of what the .head() looked like prior to filling the nas? just because the header says the first 5 are 0 doesnt mean the whole column is now 0s. if you haven't seen it already, you can check what all the values are for a column using value_counts() (look this up if it wasn't already mentioned in the LP) @Oleksandra_Aliyeva is correct, need to make a column equal to the column, otherwise you are overwriting the dataframe to be the column. another way: instead of doing .loc, you could also just do like a df['column'].fillna(0, inplace = True). be careful though, as since you already above filled the NAs across the whole df the first way without specifically calling to the 2021 counts column, you will need to rerun all previous steps to essentially "undo" it. (edited)

Marco_Jimenez
Hey guys I could use a bit of input for question 5 & 6 (Titanic Data) finding the average age of those who survived and those who didn't. I'm wondering if this is an acceptable way of doing it or if I even got the right numbers lol. Anyone's input is appreciated!
Mandy_Sachs 05-Feb-22 03:20 PM
a way you can make it so you are focused just on the age, is by doing
df[survived_df2 & age_df]['Age'].mean()
this way the age column is the only column that will show. This is the same format as df['column'] as the [filter] bracket is an extension of the df when you combine it with age_df, it actually doesn't do anything as that is how you would combine/merge filters, but since survived_df2 has the age column, it doesn't isolate that column (edited)

Steven_Briggs 06-Feb-22 10:36 AM
I've searched Discord and I'm not seeing anyone asking about this so I'm offering this suggestion: When you get to the part where we are creating and saving our plotted images, I see nothing in the courseware stating where the images are stored. So I found that if you create a directory in your google drive to store images (similar to how you would have a directory for the data files) you can modify the code to save the images there. This command maps the directory: images_dir = '/content/drive/My Drive/DATA/images' Then, where you might have this: plt.savefig('MATLABlegendcutoff.png', dpi = 300) change it to this: plt.savefig(f'{images_dir}/MATLABlegendcutoff.png', dpi = 300) (edited)
Mandy_Sachs 06-Feb-22 10:36 AM
You can also just right click and save the images

Rounding Significant Digits - I was taught the following in my science classes, and would like to know if/why this would be different from our reporting in Data Science: -‚ÄúAlgebra of Significant Figures In physics, we deal with equations, and several of them involve arithmetic operations. The result of a calculation that involve an approximate measured value of quantities (i.e. values with a limited number of significant figures) must mirror the uncertainties in the original measured values. So while performing such algebraic operations on the measured values, we ensure that the result should not be more precise than the least precise value reported. So the final answer should not have more significant figures than the original data from which it was attained. Thus, when we report our result, the number of significant figures in our calculation should be the same as the number of significant figures in the least precise value.‚Äù (edited)

Could someone guide me on how to make each bar on a histogram a different color?
Chastity_Benton
Could someone guide me on how to make each bar on a histogram a different color?
Instructor_JamesI 17-Feb-22 06:13 PM
By default, histograms are not color-coded bars, due to them all being the same feature binned (vs bar plots that are different groups being compared). If you are visualizing categorical columns, try sns.countplot instead of a histogram (edited)

Hi. When we are preparing our data for machine learning, first we encode our features and then we scale? But we don't scale columns that we just encoded, right?
Oleksandra_Aliyeva
Hi. When we are preparing our data for machine learning, first we encode our features and then we scale? But we don't scale columns that we just encoded, right?
Yvon_Bilodeau 21-Feb-22 10:13 AM
Good morning Oleksandra We encode the ordinal features first, (this can be done prior to the split), then we will standardize and scale all of the numeric features (these features along with the other numeric features.) Note - we only 'fit' on the training data, and then transform the training and test data separately. In the Ordinal Features thread Steven and I discussed this briefly. (edited)

Hi Michael Because it will not cause 'data leakage' it is most expedient to encode Ordinal features prior to the Train/Test split. These then become numeric features and will handled by the StandardScaler along with the other Numeric features.

Core Project 1 - Week 5 Outlet Size 'Outlet_Size' has 2410 missing values out of 8523 rows, which is significant (28%). This is currently an object Datatype with 'Small', 'Medium', 'High' and 'NaN' values. - 1. We could leave this as an Object Datatype and replace NaN values with either 'Missing' or 'Unknown‚Äô. - 2. We could leave this as an Object Datatype and impute NaN values using SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent') - 3. We could treat this as an Ordinal Feature and replace 'Small', 'Medium', and High' values with 0, 1, and 2, then impute the NaN values with the other Numeric Features using SimpleImputer(strategy='median') for the NaN values. What are you thoughts? (edited)

Ryan_Masters
In the first core assignment in Week 6 the example code given for the mean_absolute_error() metric is mean_absolute_error(y, preds). I can't figure out from the lesson or the sklearn documentation what inputs/variables are needed for '(y, preds)'? Anyone know? (edited)
Instructor_PurviK 24-Feb-22 10:10 AM
here, you are using target and features to generate the model, in this case, LinearRegression to predict y(house price). Once the model is generated to check its efficiency you use different metrics. mean_absolute_error(y, preds) is the absolute value of the difference between the forecasted value(predicted house price value) and the actual value(actual house price (y)). you have to calculate the predicted value using model. predict() i.e. preds = model_name.predict(X_test). Now you can use this value in mean_absolute_error(y_test, preds)
Instructor_PurviK
here, you are using target and features to generate the model, in this case, LinearRegression to predict y(house price). Once the model is generated to check its efficiency you use different metrics. mean_absolute_error(y, preds) is the absolute value of the difference between the forecasted value(predicted house price value) and the actual value(actual house price (y)). you have to calculate the predicted value using model. predict() i.e. preds = model_name.predict(X_test). Now you can use this value in mean_absolute_error(y_test, preds)

Instructor_JoshJ 01-Mar-22 10:00 AM
SimpleImputer is for filling in missing values. There are no missing values in this dataset, so imputing missing values is not necessary. No need for SimpleImputer. @Yvon_Bilodeau is also correct that all features are numeric, so there is no need for OneHotEncoder. OneHotEncoder is for transforming nominal categorical variables into one-hot encoded and therefor numeric, features. As for scaling, scaling is optional for linear regression models. There are upsides and downsides. For instance, if you wanted to interpret a fitted linear regression model to see which features are most important in predicting your target, you would want to scale them and then you can rank the resulting model coefficients. On the other hand, if you wanted to interpret how much of an increase in one feature would likely affect the target, you would not want to scale the features before fitting. You would want to keep them in the original units. As for getting the most accurate predictions from a linear regression model, it's hard to say. If my goal is accurate predictions, then I usually try both scaled and unscaled data to see which works better. I hope that provides some clarity. TLDR on the Regression Metrics assignment, no preprocessing of features is technically required.
1

Ryan_Masters 01-Mar-22 12:47 PM
Is it normal for our Food Predictions' RMSE scores to be > 1000? Or is that an indication that something is awry?
Ryan_Masters
Is it normal for our Food Predictions' RMSE scores to be > 1000? Or is that an indication that something is awry?
Instructor_JoshJ 01-Mar-22 01:34 PM
RMSE is in the same units as the original target. To determine the reasonableness of error, compare it to the original units. If the range of original target values is like 1-20, then an RMSE of 1000 is definitely a problem. If the range of the original units is 1-10000 then 1000 is probably reasonable, even if it's not great. (edited)
13:35
It's MSE that gets harder to determine in this area, since it's in squared units. Housing price predictions will often have MSEs in the tens of billions.
Instructor_JoshJ

If the range of the original units is 1-10000 then 1000 is probably reasonable, even if it's not great. (edited)

Instructor_JoshJ 03-Mar-22 09:46 AM
n_estimators refers to how many separate models are working in parallel in an ensemble model. A decision tree is a single model, not an ensemble. A bagged tree or a random forest is a collection of many trees working together in parallel to solve a problem. So for those ensemble models, 'n_estimators' refers to how many decision trees they use in parallel to solve the problem. You will often see 'estimator' used to mean a predictive model. This is common especially in Scikit-Learn documentation. (edited)

Instructor_JoshJ 09-Mar-22 01:35 PM
I appreciate you finding these. It is caused by a formatting error. The Learn Platform likes to use one kind of space and the Notebooks don't like that kind of space. These errors a invisible and hard to catch! if you copy/paste it and then remove and retype all of the spaces at the beginnings of lines that indented and between lines with a blank line between them, it should fix it. The offending spaces should have a squiggly red line under them in Colab when you try to run it. At least you are building some muscle memory typing :). Silver lining! (edited)

Instructor_JoshJ 09-Mar-22 02:46 PM
Just for future reference: if anyone in the future ever gets the error message: "Input contains NaN, infinity or a value too large for dtype('float64')" It's likely that the data has missing values. Sometimes it means the data contains np.inf types (infinity), but that is much more rare. You might also see missing values called null values or na. Hence, .isna() or .isnull() NaN, or np.nan, is what NumPy fills missing data with. It's sort of a placeholder. (edited)

Michael_Mccann
for the KNN Exercise the target has three possible outcomes: male, female, immature. Should we be selecting one of those as the TRUE target/positive class and encoding them as 0, 1? (edited)
Instructor_JoshJ 10-Mar-22 11:56 AM
Fun Fact: sklearn classification models can handle categorical targets. The models will convert the classes to numbers internally and back again for predictions. If you choose to encode the target as numbers before passing them to the model, you will need to keep careful track of which numbers correspond to which classes. It is not generally necessary to one-hot encode target variables for sklearn models, though there are some advanced techniques where you might have multiple target columns. When you learn to use deep learning models there will be some instances where it will be necessary to one-hot encode your targets, but not for KNN.
Michael_Mccann
so question about general order of operations... the way the belt exam practice is worded makes me wonder if I've been doing something wrong... in the mock they have you impute NA values prior to EDA without data leakage. Are we supposed to be train/test/splitting prior to EDA? I've always addressed NAs on the whole dataset prior to my EDA and then come back after EDA and done the train test split after re-imputing NA's from a fresh dataset at this point to avoid leakage. (edited)
Instructor_JoshJ 10-Mar-22 11:59 AM
Never impute the missing values in data you will be using for machine learning before you perform you train/test split. You may use 2 versions of the dataset, one for EDA where you impute values and a separate one for model development where you impute the values after. Imputing values before the train-test split causes information from the testing data to leak into the training data. That's cheating! Your model should never get to peak at anything directly related to the testing data, such as means, medians, or most frequent categories..

Instructor_JoshJ 10-Mar-22 01:11 PM
You can do df_ml = df.copy() Then do your EDA on df The do your X, y, and train/test split on df_ml.
Instructor_JoshJ 10-Mar-22 01:56 PM
Make sure you do the .copy(). If you just do df_ml = df, then changes in df will also appear in df_ml. In fact, both variables will point to the same dataframe!

Instructor_JoshJ 15-Mar-22 12:03 PM
I would like to make some recommendations for your Project 2. This project is intended to be the big portfolio piece for your Github portfolio. This is what you will show employers that want to know what quality of work they can expect from you. 1. Don't name your repo Project2. Once you choose yoru dataset, change the name to be relevant to the data. Similarly, don't name the notebooks 'part1, part2' etc. Pretend that this is not a class assignment, but a professional project you are doing. Remember that your real audience is not us, your instructors, but future employers. 2. Make this project shine. Again, show employers what you want them to see about you as a professional. Use section headings in your notebooks, make sure your repo is clean and well organized, and create a brief an informative readme that describes the project. 3. Communication counts. Use your best English writing skills for explanatory text, readme, section headings, etc. The #1 thing many employers are looking for is people that can communicate clearly about the technical aspects of data science to non-technical audiences. They will judge you on your writing. Proof-read and have others proof it for you, too, if you need to.

Yvon_Bilodeau 18-Mar-22 08:06 AM
Good morning Raged! Ô∏è
08:10
Below are some of the considerations I used to select the strategy for one of my numeric columns with missing values... - Missing Values: 117 (4.9)% - Outliers: 0 (0.0)% low, 0 (0.0)% high - Unique values: 14 Missing Value Options and Considerations - Drop column - con: This would result in a significant loss of data. - 4.9% missing values is not significant enough to justify this option. - Drop rows with missing values - con: This would result in a significant loss of data. - 4.9% missing rows is too significant to justify this option. - Simple Imputation using strategy = 'mean' - pro: This typically works well small numeric datasets. - con: This can introduce bias and is affected by skew and outliers more than the 'median' value. - con: This will not factor correlations between features. - Simple Imputation using strategy = 'median' - pro: This typically works well small numeric datasets. - pro: This is less affected by skew and outliers than strategy = 'median'. - con: This will not factor correlations between features. - Advanced Imputation using SKLearn - pro: This will factor correlations between features. - pro: This may have the potential to generate the highest prediction scores possible. - con: This can be memory and or time intensive.. For the scope of this project I will utilize the (Simple Imputation using strategy = 'median') method as the initial strategy. However it is recommended that others strategies be explored to see if prediction accuracy can be improved. (edited)

Yvon_Bilodeau 18-Mar-22 08:21 AM
- Drop column: no (data loss is too significant) - Drop rows: no (15% data loss is too significant) - Simple Imputation - replace with mean - Simple Imputation - replace with median - Advanced Imputation with SkLearn Is your numeric feature dispersion skewed, or does it have outliers? If is has outliers or is skewed, 'mean' will introduce more bias than 'median'. Ultimately you will want to experiment to see which strategy provides the greatest predictability for this specific dataset. (edited)

Ultimately, we may need to consult a Subject Matter Expert for the data that we are evaluating. For the plot I generated above, I chose K=5. (edited)

We talked in class last stack about how KNN works best when k is odd. One way to create a range of odd numbers is: krange = range(1,20,2) The 3rd number is the step size. So the above code will create a range between 1 and 19 with with a step size of 2. So, [1,3,5,7...]

TA_DavidN 29-Mar-22 06:52 PM
I heard some good discussions today, glad to see so many solid thoughts and opinions on the ethical dilemmas that the usage of data can potentially cause. Like so many answers in data science, many times "it depends" on the use case as to what the "right" answer might be.
18:58
I actually had a little "aha" moment today-- because so many times we can be afraid of machines and algorithms, so we think about how to limit their damage and think oh we need to make sure this is done the "old fashioned" way, or with a human touch. But since humans are limited by emotion, experiences, imperfect perceptions, recency biases and other potential problems, sometimes seeing the result of ML models can provide surprising insights to what the data shows. That is assuming the data inputted is good data, of course.

I'd like to offer you some perspective. The purpose of this project is not to show potential employers that you can solve a particular problem. The purpose is to show them that you can use professional tools to do thorough and valid data science work, that you understand what you are doing, and that you can produce high quality reports and clean, correct, readable code. Focus on having excellent process and reporting and don't worry so much as about having the best results. Most data science projects in the real world never produce anything of value anyway. Get to know your data deeply, find interesting trends to report, show off that you know how to process data, choose a model, and validate a model. Then be honest about the results. If your model doesn't perform well, just say that in your summary, explain what kinds of errors it's making and why you think that is, and suggest some next steps that might help it improve.

Instructor_JoshJ 01-Apr-22 12:17 PM
One thing to consider when doing feature selection is whether those features are likely to apply to new data when you model is deployed. If designers are included as categories, are new games that this model will be predicting likely to be created by those designers? Even more relevant, if the model learns that games by some designers tend to be more successful than games by other designers, then the model will be biased based on the name of the designer or publisher or whatever. Do you want your model to learn to be biased toward certain publishers or designers? We want to think critically about each feature we are including and ask ourselves A. will it be relevant to new data, and B. is it something we want to be used by our model to make predictions, i.e. do we want to introduce that bias?

Instructor_JoshJ 12-Apr-22 03:29 PM
Just a little perspective: Your Project 2 is probably going to as important or more important to your chances of getting hired after graduating from this program than you certificate of completion. It's one of the most important things you will leave here with. Employers usually look at applicants' portfolios of work as the most important indication of what kind of work they would do for a company that hired them. I recommend NOT treating it like a school project just get get a passing grade on, but as a demonstration of the kind of work you would do for someone who hired you. For example: your project readme will be the first, and maybe last thing that an employer looks at. Ask yourself. Will it hook them? will it make them want to see more? Does it represent your best work, summarize your project, and communicate your purpose and results clearly? What have you named your files? Is it 'part 1, part 2, part 3?' Does it look like a school project or does it look like a professional project? Your future may literally ride on the quality of that project. That said, don't forget that you can continue working on it AFTER you graduate! Personally, I put about 4 more months of work into my capstone project after graduating to make sure it showed solid professional data science skills. (edited)

Instructor_PurviK 13-Apr-22 04:16 PM
Hello Ninjas! It has been observed during grading of Neural Network Kaggle exercise that many of you are performing preprocessing on your test data. If you are doing all the preprocessing steps on your test data means you are leaking data.  In your kaggle exercise you have two separate dataset: Train data and Test data. Once you perform all the preprocessing on your Train data and build the model , you just have to load the Test data which does not include Target.  Perform the transformation on your Test data with transformer.transform(Test_df) and get the predictions using model.predict(Test_df).  Now based on your submission requirements you have to submit csv file with your predictions and appropriate id by creating the new dataframe.

Good morning Halima! Ô∏è Yes, I ran into that problem as well. It can happen when Bash windows are closed without terminating existing processes, (Windows believes there are processes still running). I closed and restarted everything. However the following articles suggests you only need to ... 1. Close the Git Bash window. 2. Open Task manager. 3. Find the ‚ÄòGit for Windows‚Äô process. 4. Kill it. 5. Open Git Bash. https://doc.xuwenliang.com/docs/git/4064 (edited)
Git bash Error: Could not fork child process: - Powered by MinDoc

your with open statement shows
with open(filename, 'r+') as file:
whereas the first shows
with open(filename, 'r+') as f:

file.seek(0)

Jacob_Lloyd 29-Apr-22 08:15 PM
Starting your file string without a slash indicates to the computer to look in the current directory
20:15
So as of right now your program is looking for a folder inside of the folder you're in named "Users"
20:15
The simple fix would be add "/" in front of "Users" (edited)

Good morning Michael! Ô∏è Phase 2 - TMDB EDA The shareholder requested a sample of only movies from 2000 and 2001 with financial information, revenue or budget be included in the csv file. SELECT certification, revenue FROM tmdb_data WHERE revenue > 0 AND certification IS NOT NULL

"Movie Legends Revealed | Did 'Star Wars' Add a Severed Arm to Earn a PG Rating?" - CBR Website Article "Star wars IV A New Hope" received a G initially. "There was a split among the ratings board, but eventually it settled upon G. Fox decided on an unusual gambit: The studio resubmitted the film and requested that it receive the stricter rating. Executives wanted a PG rating, partly because they felt some of the scenes DID seem too graphic for very young viewers and didn't wish to hear parents later complain, but primarily because they felt that the G rating by this time was seen as "uncool" and a sort of box-office poison for a non-animated film." - (edited)
